english:
  title: Inscription on the Hall of Eternal Correctness, with Preface
  author: Lee Cham
  language: eng
  text: |-
    PREFACE

    What endures long and remains firm—this is the Way of Heaven and Earth. What endures long is boundless through ten thousand ages; what remains firm governs all affairs and becomes their root. The work of Heaven's covering and Earth's support rests in what endures long; the primordial virtue among the Four Virtues is perfected in what is correct and firm. Humans are born embodying the mean of Heaven and Earth; thus the significance of eternal correctness is already present within our nature. When the world glows with ornament, rituals and laws readily change—yet to maintain what is right while lasting long proves difficult. Therefore, the superior person facing such times must make constancy and eternal correctness their foremost concern. The sage who composed the Changes feared that people would not persevere in their virtue. Thus the third line of the Adornment hexagram states: "Adorned as if drenched—eternal correctness brings good fortune." How profound is this warning! The human heart knows no constancy and easily loses its rectitude. How much more so when caught in the splendor of adornment, with its glittering light and glistening sheen? When things align through improper correspondences and create ornament, should we not heed this as a caution? Master Park of Baosan named his study hall "Eternal Correctness," drawing upon this very meaning. The way to conduct oneself amid adornment extends no further than this. Therefore I compose this inscription as a warning.

    INSCRIPTION

    Heaven's Way never ceases—
    Origin, prosperity, advantage, correctness.
    Correctness and firmness root all affairs;
    ten thousand things come to completion.
    The Changes names such virtue
    to illuminate our nature and spirit.
    The wise maintain constancy,
    preserving reverent heart.
    When Adornment's Way flourishes,
    face it with rectitude.
    In all moments, without fail,
    remember Heaven's luminous mandate.
    Why do later generations
    revere only glitter and falsehood?
    Misguided, they force change
    and corrupt simplicity's way.
    Few possess the strength to endure
    and achieve what is true.
    But our teacher has both learning and resolve.
    I inscribe this upon his study hall
    to be his constant reminder—
    that thought turn always here,
    so his name may not fade with time.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The 'Four Virtues' (四德) refer to Origin (元), Prosperity (亨), Advantage (利), and Correctness (貞)—the traditional virtues enumerated in the I Ching.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'Adornment hexagram' (賁卦) is the 22nd hexagram of the I Ching, representing ornament, decoration, or cultural refinement.
  - key: ''
    value: The phrase 'Adorned as if drenched' alludes to the need to balance outward form with inner substance, much like how ornament must not overwhelm true character.
